{Begin with 1.d4. The goal is not to memorize one fixed sequence, but to recognize which London structure fits Black's setup.}
1. d4
{White claims central space and keeps the c-pawn flexible. The next priority is usually to develop the c1 bishop before playing e3.}
1... d5
{Black has established a pawn on d5. Watch the c8 bishop and the rest of Black's center before choosing c3 or c4.}
(1... c5
{Black has challenged the center before playing d5. Do not force a normal London triangle; take space immediately.}
2. d5
{This creates a Benoni-style space advantage. White will follow with Nc3 and e4 instead of c3.}
2... Nf6
{Black attacks the center and prepares normal development. Build support behind the advanced d5 pawn.}
3. Nc3
{The b1 knight belongs on c3 because White intends a broad center with e4.}
3... d6
{Black prepares to challenge the advanced center. Reinforce it with another pawn.}
4. e4
{White now has the broad d5-e4 center.}
4... g6
{Black is preparing a kingside fianchetto. Continue development without abandoning the center.}
5. Nf3
{The kingside knight supports e5 and helps White castle.}
5... Bg7
{Black completes the fianchetto. The light-squared bishop is usually more useful on e2 than d3 here.}
6. Be2
{Be2 develops safely without aiming at an h7 target that the fianchetto has changed.}
6... O-O
{Black has secured the king. White should do the same.}
7. O-O
{White reaches a sound Benoni-style development with extra central space.})
(1... Nf6
{Black develops without committing the center. White can still begin with the London bishop.}
2. Bf4
{The bishop develops outside the pawn chain before e3 closes it in.}
2... d5
{Black has now established d5. Look for whether Black chooses a quiet setup, a fianchetto, or a slow move that permits fork preparation.}
    (2... g6
    {Black is committing to a kingside fianchetto. This is a signal to use Nc3 and build e4 rather than play the quiet c3 London.}
    3. Nc3
    {Nc3 supports the broad center and keeps the option of e4 immediate.}
    3... Bg7
    {The fianchetto is complete. Claim more central space before Black strikes back.}
    4. e4
    {White builds the active Nc3-e4 structure.}
    4... d6
    {Black supports e5 and prepares development. White should coordinate the queen and king for the attacking setup.}
    5. Qd2
    {Qd2 connects the pieces, supports Bh6 ideas, and prepares queenside castling.}
    5... O-O
    {Black castles kingside. White may now castle the opposite way because the structure is committed.}
    6. O-O-O
    {Opposite-side castling supports a direct kingside attack, provided the queenside remains stable.}
    6... c5
    {Black challenges the center. Preserve space and close the center when appropriate.}
    7. d5
    {The center closes, giving White room to build a kingside attack.})
    (2... b6
    {Black is preparing to fianchetto the c8 bishop. Use active central development rather than automatically choosing c3.}
    3. Nc3
    {Nc3 supports central expansion and keeps e4 available.}
    3... d5
    {Black establishes a central pawn. White can now support d4 without giving up the active knight placement.}
    4. e3
    {e3 supports d4 and opens the f1 bishop.}
    4... Bb7
    {Black's bishop now controls the long diagonal. Continue normal development and prepare to meet a bishop challenge.}
    5. Nf3
    {Nf3 supports the center and prepares castling.}
    5... e6
    {Black completes a solid center. Develop the remaining bishop toward the kingside.}
    6. Bd3
    {Bd3 points toward h7 and supports normal London attacking ideas.}
    6... Bd6
    {Black is trying to exchange the London bishop. Preserve it because it controls important attacking squares.}
    7. Bg3
    {Bg3 keeps the bishop and maintains control of e5 and the diagonal toward c7.}
    7... O-O
    {Black castles. White should finish king safety.}
    8. O-O
    {White completes development with the London bishop preserved.})
    3. e3
    {With no immediate structural trigger, support d4 and open the kingside bishop.}
    3... h6
    {Black has spent a slow tempo. Check whether the c7 fork geometry can be prepared before Black castles.}
    4. Nc3
    {Nc3 places the knight on the route to b5 while Bf4 protects c7.}
    4... e6
    {Black still has the king on e8, the rook on a8, and the pawn on c7. The fork setup is alive.}
    5. Nb5
    {Nb5 threatens Nxc7+, a checking fork of the king and a8 rook.}
    5... Na6
    {Black has defended c7 with the knight. Do not force the fork now; resume development.}
        (5... Be7
        {Black develops but does not defend c7 or remove the bishop on f4. The fork is ready.}
        6. Nxc7+
        {Nxc7+ forks the king and rook while the bishop on f4 supports the knight.}
        6... Kf8
        {The king moves, leaving the rook on a8 available. Complete the tactic.}
        7. Nxa8
        {White wins the rook and finishes the fork sequence.})
        (5... c6
        {The c-pawn attacks the knight and removes the c7 target. The fork has disappeared, so retreat.}
        6. Nc3
        {Return the knight to c3 and continue with a normal position.})
        (5... Bb4+
        {Black gives a forcing check and interrupts the fork. Answer the check before continuing development.}
        6. c3
        {c3 blocks the check and attacks the bishop while building a stable center.}
        6... Be7
        {The check is resolved and the fork is no longer urgent. Continue development.}
        7. Nf3
        {Nf3 supports the center and prepares castling.}
        7... O-O
        {Black reaches safety.})
        (5... Bd6
        {Black attacks the bishop that supports c7. Preserve the bishop before reconsidering the fork.}
        6. Bg3
        {The bishop retreats while maintaining useful control.}
        6... Bxg3
        {Black chooses to exchange the bishop. Recapture with the h-pawn.}
        7. hxg3
        {The h-pawn recaptures and opens the h-file, but the original fork support is gone.})
    6. Nf3
    {Since c7 is defended, return to normal development.}
    6... c6
    {Black attacks the knight on b5 and removes the c7 target. Retreat the knight.}
    7. Nc3
    {The knight returns to its useful central square.}
    7... Bd6
    {Black challenges the London bishop. Preserve it.}
    8. Bg3
    {Bg3 keeps the bishop and completes the tactical lesson: prepare the fork only while the geometry remains favorable.}
    8... O-O)
2. Bf4
{Develop the London bishop before e3.}
2... Nf6
{Black develops normally. White can support d4 unless a more urgent structural signal appears.}
(2... c5
{Black challenges d4 after already playing d5. Support the center first, then choose a stable response to later pressure.}
3. e3
{e3 reinforces d4 and keeps both c3 and c4 available for the moment.}
3... Nc6
{Black adds pressure to d4. Develop the kingside knight.}
4. Nf3
{Nf3 supports d4 and prepares castling.}
4... Nf6
{Black completes normal development. The b1 knight can now support the quiet structure from d2.}
5. Nbd2
{Nbd2 pairs naturally with a future c3 London triangle.}
5... Qb6
{Black attacks b2 and increases pressure on d4. This concrete threat overrides automatic development.}
6. Qc1
{Qc1 defends b2 without abandoning the London structure.}
6... e6
{Black stabilizes the center. White can now complete the pawn triangle.}
7. c3
{c3 reinforces d4 and creates the traditional London structure.}
7... Be7
{Black continues development. Place the remaining bishop actively.}
8. Bd3
{Bd3 points toward h7 and supports kingside play.}
8... O-O
{Black castles. White should secure the king.}
9. O-O
{White completes a solid setup after meeting the early queen pressure.})
(2... Bf5
{Black develops the c8 bishop before securing it with e6. The bishop has left b7 undefended, so prepare an active c4 setup.}
3. e3
{Support d4 and open the f1 bishop before committing the c-pawn.}
3... Nf6
{Black develops normally, but the early bishop placement still favors c4.}
4. c4
{c4 attacks d5 and chooses the active London structure instead of c3.}
4... e6
{Black supports d5. The b1 knight now belongs on c3.}
5. Nc3
{Nc3 supports the c4 pressure and develops toward active play.}
5... c6
{Black builds a Slav-style center. The c8 bishop is gone, so b7 is a real target.}
6. Qb3
{Qb3 pressures b7 while the c4 pawn attacks d5.}
6... Qb6
{Black offers a queen exchange while defending b7. Accepting it is comfortable.}
7. Qxb6
{The queen exchange removes Black's active queen and preserves White's structural pressure.}
7... axb6
{Black recaptures with the a-pawn, creating doubled queenside pawns. Continue development.}
8. Nf3
{Nf3 develops and prepares castling.}
8... Nbd7
{Black completes development. The light-squared bishop belongs safely on e2 in this active structure.}
9. Be2
{Be2 develops without blocking the queen's former pressure line or inviting unnecessary exchanges.}
9... Be7
{Black prepares to castle. White should do the same.}
10. O-O
{White reaches a sound active London middlegame with pressure and easy development.}
10... O-O)
(2... e6
